<subsection xml:id="subsec-introduction-to-similarity" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Introduction to Similarity</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.1 Similarity and Enlargement
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Determine the centre of enlargement and the linear scale factor for similar figures
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define similarity and identify the conditions for two shapes to be similar (equal corresponding angles and proportional corresponding sides).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Calculate unknown side lengths and angles in similar triangles using ratios of corresponding sides.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Apply the concept of similarity and enlargement to solve real-world problems involving maps, models, photographs, and architectural drawings.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/similarity-and-enlargement/introduction-to-similarity.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/similarity-and-enlargement/step-by-step-guide_introduction-to-similarity.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery (15 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Exploring Similar Triangles</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Work in pairs.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Instructions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol markers="1.">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Draw <m>\triangle ABC</m> with <m>AB = 7</m> cm, <m>AC = 6</m> cm, <m>BC = 5</m> cm. Label the angles: <m>\angle ABC = 50^\circ</m>, <m>\angle BAC = 60^\circ</m>, <m>\angle BCA = 70^\circ</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Draw <m>\triangle PQR</m> with <m>PQ = 21</m> cm, <m>PR = 18</m> cm, <m>QR = 15</m> cm. Label the angles: <m>\angle PQR = 50^\circ</m>, <m>\angle QRP = 70^\circ</m>, <m>\angle QPR = 60^\circ</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Find the ratios of corresponding sides:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>\frac{QR}{BC} \amp = \frac{15}{5} = 3</mrow>
                            <mrow>\frac{PQ}{AB} \amp = \frac{21}{7} = 3</mrow>
                            <mrow>\frac{PR}{AC} \amp = \frac{18}{6} = 3</mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Notice that all ratios are equal to 3, and corresponding angles are equal. Triangle <m>PQR</m> is an enlargement of triangle <m>ABC</m> with scale factor 3.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teacher Questions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <q>What pattern do you see in the ratios?</q>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <q>Are the angles the same in both triangles?</q>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Expected Responses:</alert> All ratios equal 3, corresponding angles are equal, so the triangles are similar.
        </p>
    </axiom>

