    <figure xml:id="interactive-similarity-intro">
        <caption>Interactive Exploration of Similar Triangles</caption>
        <interactive xml:id="similarity-intro" platform="jsxgraph" width="100%" aspect="4:3" source="jsxgraph/similarity-intro.js">
            <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-similarity-intro" surface="jsxboard" aspect="4:3" />
            <instructions xml:id="similarity-intro-instructions">
                <p>
                    In this interactive, triangle <m>ABC</m> is the original triangle. 
                    You may click and drag vertices <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m> to change its shape, expand it, or shrink it.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Triangle <m>PQR</m> is constructed to be similar to triangle <m>ABC</m>. 
                    Use the slider at the top to change the scale factor <m>k</m>, which enlarges or reduces triangle <m>PQR</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The angle measures of both triangles are displayed. 
                    As you manipulate the triangles, observe carefully:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>What happens to the side lengths?</li>
                        <li>What happens to the angle measures?</li>
                        <li>Which properties stay the same even when the size changes?</li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </instructions>
        </interactive>
    </figure>
    <insight>
        <p xml:id="auto_fg7f1vco">
            <ul xml:id="auto_8bf77swk">
                <li xml:id="auto_wznygwyg">
                    <p xml:id="auto_bqxb8bph">
                        Two triangles are similar if their corresponding angles are equal and their corresponding sides are in the same ratio.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li xml:id="auto_f37q8inw">
                    <p xml:id="auto_falz2jpb">
                        Similarity refers to a relationship between two shapes or figures where one can be transformed into the other through scaling (enlargement or reduction), without changing its shape. 
                    The two shapes are similar if they have the same shape but may differ in size.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Guided Practice (10 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Problem 1:</alert> Triangles <m>PQR</m> and <m>ABC</m> are similar. Given <m>AB = 6</m> cm, <m>AC = 9</m> cm, <m>PR = 12</m> cm, and <m>QR = 14</m> cm. Find <m>BC</m> (marked <m>x</m>) and <m>PQ</m> (marked <m>y</m>).
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Solution:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow>\frac{AB}{PQ} \amp = \frac{AC}{PR} = \frac{BC}{QR}</mrow>
                <mrow>\frac{6}{y} \amp = \frac{9}{12} = \frac{x}{14}</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            Solving for <m>y</m>:
            <md>
                <mrow>\frac{6}{y} \amp = \frac{9}{12}</mrow>
                <mrow>9y \amp = 72</mrow>
                <mrow>y \amp = 8 \text{ cm}</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            Solving for <m>x</m>:
            <md>
                <mrow>\frac{9}{12} \amp = \frac{x}{14}</mrow>
                <mrow>12x \amp = 126</mrow>
                <mrow>x \amp = 10.5 \text{ cm}</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Problem 2:</alert> Triangles <m>XYZ</m> and <m>PQR</m> are similar. Given <m>\angle ZYX = 72^\circ</m>, <m>\angle YZX = 61^\circ</m>, <m>YZ = 16</m> cm, <m>PQ = 40</m> cm, and <m>XY = 12</m> cm. Find <m>\angle QPR</m>, <m>\angle PQR</m>, and the length of <m>PR</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Solution:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            Since the triangles are similar, corresponding angles are equal:
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p><m>\angle QPR = \angle ZYX = 72^\circ</m></p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p><m>\angle PQR = \angle YZX = 61^\circ</m></p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            Finding <m>PR</m>:
            <md>
                <mrow>\frac{YZ}{PQ} \amp = \frac{XY}{PR}</mrow>
                <mrow>\frac{16}{40} \amp = \frac{12}{PR}</mrow>
                <mrow>16 \times PR \amp = 40 \times 12</mrow>
                <mrow>PR \amp = \frac{480}{16} = 30 \text{ cm}</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_i9u5j6ut">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_qti1dx1b">
                
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_3l6yfe8e">
                In the figure below, the triangles <m>PQR</m> and <m>ABC</m> are similar. Calculate the lengths marked with letters <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.
            </p>

            <sidebyside>
                <image>
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    <latex-image label="similar-triangle1">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % Triangle ABC (Blue fill)
                        \fill[blue!30] (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (2,3.5) -- cycle;  % Light blue fill
                        \draw[thick, blue] (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (2,3.5) -- cycle;
                        
                        % Labels for triangle ABC
                        \node[left] at (0,0) {A};
                        \node[right] at (5,0) {B};
                        \node[above] at (2,3.5) {C};
                        \node[below] at (2.5,0) {6 cm};
                        \node[left] at (1,2) {9 cm};
                        \node[right] at (3.5,2) {x};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                    
                </image>

                <image>
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    <latex-image label="similar-triangle2">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                              % % Define triangle vertices
                    \coordinate (P) at (0,0);
                    \coordinate (Q) at (5,0);
                    \coordinate (R) at (1,3);

                    % Draw and fill the triangle
                    \draw[thick, fill=red, opacity=0.5] (P) -- (Q) -- (R) -- cycle;

                    % Label vertices
                    \node[above] at (R) {R};  
                    \node[below left] at (P) {P};  
                    \node[below right] at (Q) {Q};  

                    % Label sides
                    \node[below] at ($(P)!0.5!(Q)$) {y };  % Midpoint of PQ
                    \node[right] at ($(Q)!0.5!(R)$) {14 cm};  % Midpoint of QR
                    \node[left] at ($(P)!0.5!(R)$) {12 cm};  % Midpoint of PR
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                    
                </image>
            </sidebyside>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_lec631ly">
                <m>AB</m> corresponds to <m>PQ</m>, <m>BC</m> corresponds to <m>QR</m>, and <m>AC</m> corresponds to <m>PR</m>.
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_ff9wnd09">
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Therefore,} \amp \frac{AB}{PQ}= \frac{AC}{PR}= \frac {BC}{QR} </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{6\, cm}{y}= \frac{9\, cm}{12\, cm}= \frac {x}{14\, cm} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \frac{6\, cm}{y}=\amp \frac{9\, cm}{12\, cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow> y \times 9\, cm= \amp 6\, cm \times 12\, cm </mrow>
                    <mrow> y= \amp \frac{72\, cm^2}{9\, cm}  </mrow>
                    <mrow> y =\amp 8\, cm </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Therefore PQ}= \amp 8 cm</mrow>
                     <mrow> \frac{9\, cm}{12\, cm}=\amp \frac{x}{14\, cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow> x \times 12\, cm= \amp 9\, cm \times 14\, cm </mrow>
                    <mrow> x= \amp \frac{126\, cm^2}{12\, cm}  </mrow>
                    <mrow> x =\amp 10.5\, cm </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Therefore BC}= \amp 10.5\, cm</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="auto_hu8w78oy">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_5bv7xd8h">
                
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_e5dj21yk">
                Given that triangles <m>XYZ</m> and <m>PQR</m> in  figure 2.1.3 are similar, Find the size of <m>\angle\, QPR</m>, <m>\angle\, PQR</m> and the length of line <m>PR</m>
            </p>

            <figure xml:id="triangle-xyz">
                <caption></caption>
            <image>
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="triangle-xyz">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Triangle ABC (Blue fill)
                        \fill[blue!30] (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (2,3.5) -- cycle;  % Light blue fill
                        \draw[thick, blue] (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (2,3.5) -- cycle;
                        
                        % Labels for triangle ABC
                        \node[left] at (0,0) {Y};
                        \node[right] at (5,0) {Z};
                        \node[above] at (2,3.5) {X};
                        \node[below] at (2.5,0) {16 cm};
                        \node[left] at (1,2) {12 cm};
                        \node[right] at (3.5,2) {14 cm};

                        % Angles
                        \draw[thick] (0.8,0) arc[start angle=0,end angle=59,radius=0.8cm];
                        \node at (1.2,0.3) {\small $72^\circ$};

                        \draw[thick] (4.2,0) arc[start angle=180,end angle=131,radius=0.8cm];
                        \node at (3.8,0.3) {\small $61^\circ$};

                        % Triangle PQR (Red fill)
                        \fill[red!30] (8,0) -- (14,0) -- (11,4) -- cycle; % Light red fill
                        \draw[thick, red] (8,0) -- (14,0) -- (11,4) -- cycle;
                        
                        % Labels for triangle PQR
                        \node[left] at (8,0) {P};
                        \node[right] at (14,0) {Q};
                        \node[above] at (11,4) {R};
                        \node[below] at (11,0) {40 cm};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>

          </figure>

            
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_6uimncpt">
                Since the two triangles are equal, then their corresponding angles must be equal 
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_xefftony">
                <m>\angle\, ZYX</m> corresponds to <m>\angle\, QPR</m>
            </p>
            
            <p xml:id="auto_7tzsx7z7">
                Since <m>\angle\, ZYX=72^\circ</m>, then 
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_5xstt0go">
                <m>\angle\, QPR= 72^\circ </m>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_61fhg5ew">
                 <m>\angle\, YZX</m> corresponds to <m>\angle\, PQR</m>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_vnjxydw2">
                Since <m>\angle\, YZX=61^\circ</m>, then 
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_md118ui3">
                <m>\angle\, PQR= 61^\circ </m>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_wl6u6i6i">
                Now to find the length of <m>PQ</m>, We use the concept of similarity
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_wkgkb2m0">
                <md>
                    <mrow>\frac{YZ}{PQ} =\amp\frac{XY}{PR} </mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac{16}{40}= \amp \frac{12}{PR}</mrow>
                    <mrow> PR \times 16= \amp 40 \times 12</mrow>
                    <mrow>PR= \amp \frac{480}{16}</mrow>
                    <mrow>PR= \amp 30\, cm</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    
